======================================================================
WALSH-GAUSS STRUCTURE ANALYSIS
======================================================================

============================================================
p = 7, m = 3, QR = [1, 2, 4]
============================================================

  H distribution (counts symmetric orientations):
    H = 175: 6 orientations (x2 with symmetry = 12)
    H = 189: 2 orientations (x2 with symmetry = 4)

  Degree-2 Walsh coefficients:
    (0, 1): gaps=(1,2), q=3, h_hat=      7.0000, |h_hat|=      7.0000, chi(prod)=+1, sign=OK
    (0, 2): gaps=(1,3), q=3, h_hat=     -7.0000, |h_hat|=      7.0000, chi(prod)=-1, sign=OK
    (1, 2): gaps=(2,3), q=3, h_hat=     -7.0000, |h_hat|=      7.0000, chi(prod)=-1, sign=OK

  |h_hat| by resonance level:
    q=3 (chi(q)=-1): |h_hat| = [7.0]

  --- MAGNITUDE RATIOS ---

  --- D^{2n} DECOMPOSITION ---
  h_hat[{a,b}] = sum_n D^{2n}_ab / 2^m
  For q-resonant pair: D^{2n}_ab nonzero only at n >= (q+1)/2
  Sign of D^{2n} at onset: chi(q) * chi(ab)

    q=3: onset at D^4, sign(D^4) = chi(q)*chi(ab) = (-1)*(+1) = -1
    h_hat =       7.0000, sign(h_hat) = +1, chi(ab) = +1
    => D^4 has WRONG sign for product law!
       But h_hat still has correct sign => higher D^{2n} or OCF nonlinearity corrects it


